entry.title: Remove `enable_rust_qr` build flag.
entry.content:
QR code generator implemented in Rust has shipped to Windows, MacOS,

Linux, and Android (see https://crrev.com/c/5061588) and is launching to

ChromeOS. This means that soon Rust toolchain will be required to build

QR support in Chrome - this CL makes an early, small step in this

direction by removing the `enable_rust_qr` build flag.



Removing the `enable_rust_qr` build flag is a prerequisite for removing

the C++ implementation of the QR code generator. Removal of the C++

implementation will not happen until ChromeOS launch process completes

(hopefully in a month or so) but removing the `enable_rust_qr` build

flag early should help to flush out any potential issues early (e.g.

help to identify places where Rust toolchain needs to be added in

third-party builds of Chromium).

entry.title: [reland 2] on-device: enables enable_ml_internal
entry.content:
Specifically for branded desktop builds.



The most recent reland was reverted because building with

build_with_internal_optimization_guide false and

enable_ml_internal true caused build problems. This reland

sets enable_ml_internal to true only if

build_with_internal_optimization_guide is true. For the time

being the two aren't always the same (chromeos/android). At

some point they should be compiled.





The original change was reverted because of compile issues with

win-arm and mac-intel. This disables the win-arm config (for the

moment). The mac-intel failure is twofold:

1. Some of the optimization-guide code is including tflite, and needs

to inherit the gn config from neon_2_sse.

Specifically the file neon_check.h has the include:

This only works with the neon_2_sse config, which adds the right

include dir.

2. With (1) fixed, NEON_2_SSE.h generates errors that require

"-Wno-gnu-inline-cpp-without-extern." Disabling this is already

in tflite_flags, but it really belongs in neon2 as that is the

place with the issue.



The fix for 1&2 is only done for the standalone target as we don't

want to add public configs to targets that disable compiler warnings.





Bug b:308802463

`ET_SCROLL_FLING_START` or `ET_GESTURE_SWIPE`, but the function

prioritize fixing bugs for pinch resize, so this change reverts

entry.title: pip-pinch: Revert resistance effect of pinch resize
entry.content:
The PiP team has decided that we should disable the resistance

effect of pinch resize due to the bugs and maintenance costs.



For context, the primary reason why the effect doesn't work well

especially with ARC PiP is that it needs to synchronize transform

and bounds animations at the end of drag, but it's really hard to

do so because only the bounds change goes through ARC. Currently,

we preemptively apply bounds animation and sync the final bounds

to ARC, but it contradicts the concept of client-controlled, and

in fact, it may not be done properly in some edge cases.



This change is effectively the revert of crrev.com/c/4833011 and

crrev.com/c/4923231, but due to the amount of merge conflicts,

this change manually remove the logic related to the effect.



Bug: b/313024926

Test: Manually verified that the effect was disabled, and all the

bugs related to them were gone.

events.



The shortcut customization app currently utilizes javascript's built-in

input key handler for displaying and sending key events back to the

AcceleratorConfigurationProvider.



This has notable downsides including:

represent what keys are pressed/released

- Lack of flexibility with handling key input events

- Lack of additional key data fields (domcodes, domkeys, etc)



This change allows for the shortcut customization app to accurately

display what keys are pressed/released. By also controlling the

input events ourselves, we can manipulate and modify key events to our

needs. For example, using domcodes to remap positional keys.

entry.title: Increase priority of frames capturing audio
entry.content:
When the `PMProcessPriorityPolicy` feature is enabled, the priority of

processes will be controlled by the Performance Manager. This code path

is currently off by default.



This CL future-proofs a code path for when the `PMProcessPriorityPolicy`

flag gets turned on. It increases the priority of tabs capturing

MediaStreams from USER_VISIBLE to USER_BLOCKING, to match the priority

of tabs playing out audio (see FrameAudibleVoter).



Note that USER_VISIBLE and USER_BLOCKING both map to the same process

priority for now, but there might be a distinction in the future.

entry.title: [2nd attempt] Deflake+reenable `ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle`.
entry.content:
Before this CL, the test would not control the timing of



1. DOMContentLoaded event. This meant that script registration might

happen more than 200ms after DOMContentLoaded - after the window

where `document_idle` timing would be effective

2. Script-loaded event. This means that a slow file IO in the browser

process could mean that the script will get registered after

the `document_idle` time window.



After this CL:



A. The test uses a single frame and no subframes - controlling the

timing of DOMContentLoaded of the main frame (via

ControllableHttpResponse) is sufficient.

B. The test explicitly waits until the content script gets loaded.



The earlier, unsuccessful deflaking attempt can be found in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5038655

The current attempt was tested via:

* Local run, repeated 50 times

* Manually scheduling 7 runs of linux_chromium_dbg_ng

entry.title: [Extensions] Modify some Automation API tests to use service workers.
entry.content:
Because tests for service worker-based extensions must have a

background page, this CL rearranges these tests as follows:



1. Instead of loading an HTML page that loads a common script and the

test script, a custom extension is generated with all of the common

code in the main background page script.



2. The main background page then loads the test JS file using

chrome.test.loadScript.



3. The test script then calls into a common function with an array

of test functions to be run.



This has the advantage of avoiding the creation of separate test

extensions in chrome/test/data/extensions/api_test/automation and

only requires minor tweaks to the test JS file. The common JS file

and the html files that previously were used to launch the tests are

deleted.
